    <item>
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/01-introduction/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Aug 2018 10:53:26 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/01-introduction/</guid>
      <description>Hyper-Text Markup Language (HTML) alongside Hyper-Text Transfer Protocol (HTTP) formed the core of Sir Tim Berners-Lee’s world-wide web. As the name implies, HTTP is a markup language, one that combines the text of what is being said with instructions on how to display it.&#xA;The other aspect of HTML is its hyper-text nature. Hyper-text refers to text that links to additional resources - primarily the links in the document, but also embedded multimedia.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>HTML Element Structure</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/02-element-structure/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Aug 2018 10:53:26 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/02-element-structure/</guid>
      <description>HTML was built from the SGML (Structured Generalized Markup Language) standard, which provides the concept of “tags” to provide markup and structure within a text document. Each element in HTML is defined by a unique opening and closing tag, which in turn are surrounded by angle brackets (&lt;&gt;).&#xA;For example, a top-level heading in HTML would be written:&#xA;&lt;h1&gt;Hello World&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;And render:&#xA;Hello World The &lt;h1&gt; is the opening tag and the &lt;/h1&gt; is the closing tag.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>HTML Document Structure</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/03-document-structure/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Aug 2018 10:53:26 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/03-document-structure/</guid>
      <description>When authoring an HTML page, HTML elements should be organized into an HTML Document. This format is defined in the HTML standard. HTML that does not follow this format are technically invalid, and may not be interpreted and rendered correctly by all browsers. Accordingly, it is important to follow the standard.&#xA;The basic structure of a valid HTML5 document is:&#xA;&lt;!doctype HTML&gt; &lt;html lang=&#34;en&#34;&gt; &lt;head&gt; &lt;title&gt;Page Title Goes Here&lt;/title&gt; &lt;/head&gt; &lt;body&gt; &lt;p&gt;Page body and tags go here.</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Flow Model</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/04-flow-model/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Aug 2018 10:53:26 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/04-flow-model/</guid>
      <description>Given that the role of HTML is markup, i.e. providing structure and formatting to text, HTML elements can broadly be categorized into two categories depending on how they affect the flow of text - inline and block.&#xA;Inline elements referred to elements that maintained the flow of text, i.e. the bring attention to (&lt;b&gt;) element used in a paragraph of text, would bold the text without breaking the flow:&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The quick brown &lt;b&gt;fox&lt;/b&gt; lept over the log&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Tables</title>
      <link>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/05-tables/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 24 Aug 2018 10:53:26 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://textbooks.cs.ksu.edu/cc120/3-html/05-tables/</guid>
      <description>Tables were amongst the first addition to HTML (along with images), as they were necessary for the primary role of early HTML, disseminating research.&#xA;A table requires a lot of elements to be nested in a specific manner. It is best expressed through an example:&#xA;&lt;table&gt; &lt;thead&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;th&gt;Name&lt;/th&gt; &lt;th&gt;Role&lt;/th&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;/thead&gt; &lt;tbody&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Darth Vader&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Antagonist&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Luke Skywalker&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Coming-of-age protagonist&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Princess Lea&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Heroic resistance fighter&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Obi-Wan Kenobi&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Wise old man&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Han Solo&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Likeable scoundrel&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Chewbacca&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;The muscle&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Threepio&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Comedic foil&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;tr&gt; &lt;td&gt;Artoo Deetoo&lt;/td&gt; &lt;td&gt;Plot driver&lt;/td&gt; &lt;/tr&gt; &lt;/tbody&gt; &lt;/table&gt;It renders as:</description>
